        <hl2 class="online_headline">About Those Haircuts</hl2>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Democratic presidential candidate John Edwards tells reporters in Iowa that he was embarrassed over disclosure that he had paid $800 for two haircuts in California earlier this year (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>John Edwards, the North Carolina Democrat who is seeking his party's presidential nomination in 2008, told reporters in Iowa yesterday that he was ''embarrassed'' over the disclosure that he had paid $800 for two haircuts in California earlier this year.</p>
        <p>Mr. Edwards tried to joke it off while campaigning in Adel, Iowa.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="online_lead_paragraph">
        <p>John Edwards told reporters in Iowa that he was “embarrassed” over the disclosure that he had paid $800 for two haircuts.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>John Edwards, the North Carolina Democrat who is seeking his party's presidential nomination in 2008, told reporters in Iowa yesterday that he was ''embarrassed'' over the disclosure that he had paid $800 for two haircuts in California earlier this year.</p>
        <p>Mr. Edwards tried to joke it off while campaigning in Adel, Iowa.</p>
        <p>His remarks were reported by Radio Iowa. Mr. Edwards told the crowd that people want to come to America ''because people like me can come from nowhere, the son of a mill worker -- y'all have heard me say that before -- and now be running for the president of the United States and pay $400 for a haircut.'' He added, ''People around the world look at us and say, 'That's what we want. We want that kind of chance.' ''</p>
      </block>
